@The_Crimson_Fucker The designers of toys are usually childless because they are young and haven't had children yet because the design world prefers to employ people straight from art college and then get rid of them or put them in a different job when they get to 35.  I'm sure some on the design team have children.  Besides let the children have a say in the design of the toys.  Invite them to a meeting where they choose colours and prototype designs and play with the toys.  Young adults have only come out of childhood themselves in recent years so have a better idea of what children like and dislike.

Having children of your own doesn't help you to understand children.  Growing up the only relatives and friends of parents who spoke to me like an intelligent person and saw me as an individual were childless.  Because they weren't consumed with worries and cares about caring for their own children only caring for elderly parents and their careers.  They were encountering children with a fresh mind and not prejudices so were open and inquiring.  They didn't have children to unfavourably compare me with as parents often do.  My paternal grandfather would assume I liked the same foods, drinks and activities as my cousins, his other grandchildren, forgetting I was an individual.  It was because he saw more of them as they lived closer.  My paternal grandmother would ignore us and use her grandchildren to play one daughter in law off with the other, my mother and aunt by marriage.  I was only aware of that when my mother told me what was happening when I was in my teens.  On the other hand a single and childless great aunt asked me straight, when I was about ten, what I was hoping to do when I left school.  She didn't assume I wanted to be a nurse or told me what I should be doing on leaving school like the other relatives who had had children.

Parents often see other people's children through the eyes of their own children not as they are.  They judge other people's children by the standards their own children seem to set.  If their own children are studious they see other people's children who are less studious as lazy or rambuctious.  If their own children aren't studious and prefer to play, they see other people's children who are more studious and are bookworms as oppressed, lonely and/or lacking in social skills so they turn to books.  A minority of parents do admire traits in other people's children that their own children don't have but they are the exception to the rule.

